<DOC><DOCNO> AP880505-0210 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-88 1615EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i BC-Hostages-Anderson 1stLd-Writethru a0773 05-05 0185</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Hostages-Anderson, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0773,0186</SECOND><HEAD>Hostage Says He Shared Cell With Anderson</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-7 pvs, ``Anderson's sister ... with 1 graf toDELETE reference to Carton.</NOTE><DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A freed French hostage said Thursday that he hadshared a cell with American Terry Anderson during his captivity inLebanon.   Asked by a French television reporter how he felt, MarcelFontaine replied: ``We survived.''   ``I passed the time playing dominoes and chess with mycellmate,'' he added.   Asked who his companion was, Fontaine replied, ``The American,Terry Anderson.''   Anderson, 40, chief Middle East correspondent for The AssociatedPress, is the longest held of the hostages. He was kidnapped March16, 1985.   Anderson's sister, Peggy Say, said she was encouraged by thereleases. She said she planned to contact the French hostages andask ``what Terry is thinking and dreaming about, what his hopesare. How he's surviving.'' She spoke in a telephone interview withThe Associated Press from her home in Batavia, N.Y.   Fontaine, Marcel Carton and journalist Jean-Paul Kauffmannarrived in Paris Thursday after being freed a day earlier.</TEXT></DOC>